React by Namaste Akashy Saini

Using React JS Creating Heading

<body>
  <div id="root"></div>
  <script>
    let heading = document.createElement("h1");
    heading.innerHTML = "Hello World";
    let root = document.getElementById("root");
    root.appendChild(heading);
  </script>
</body>

In React

While creating an element we use:
React.createElement()

And we pass three arguments to it:
React.createElement("h1", {}, "Hello World");

Element type — "h1"

Props — {}

Children — "Hello World"

const heading = React.createElement(
  "h1",
  { id: "title" },
  "Namaste Everyone"
);

const root = ReactDOM.createRoot(document.getElementById("root"));
root.render(heading);

Note:

When we render a heading into a div using React,
or we create multiple headings inside that div using HTML,
when we render our React heading (created by React),
it will override the other HTML headings inside that div.

What is a Package?

It’s like a module or package of JavaScript files.
If we want some package into our code, then we have to use a package manager.

NPM doesn’t stand for Node Package Manager.
